The article explains the history behind Presidents' Day, which is officially known as "Washington's Birthday." The holiday originated in 1879 to honor George Washington and was later moved to the third Monday in February as part of a law mandating federal holidays to occur on Mondays. There was an attempt in 1968 to change the name to "Presidents' Day," but it was dropped due to controversy. Despite this, many states adopted the name "Presidents' Day" instead. The article also mentions how past presidents have recognized the holiday, such as Franklin Delano Roosevelt and Ronald Reagan. It concludes by highlighting the importance of remembering and celebrating George Washington's life and the values he stood for.